entry.title: Define an extensions.mojom.ServiceWorker interface
entry.content:
Push the permissions from the browser to each service worker so

that we avoid racing with the main thread when permissions

are updated.



Currently if a permission update is sent it is sent via the

extensions.mojom.Renderer interface and all these events are propagated

to the WorkerThreads. In order to unblock the ResponseWorkerAck message

from not hitting the main thread and directly going to the worker

thread (as a callback on extensions.ServiceWorkerHost.RequestWorker)

we proactively push the updated permissions on the associated channel

with the ServiceWorker. This avoids the race that will happen.



This is tested by ExtensionApiTest.EventAfterPermissionRemoved

entry.title: [omnibox][zps] Make consistent use of GetZeroSuggestInput.
entry.content:
In the course of experimenting with "ZPS prefetching on SRP" on iOS, we

uncovered a bug whereby the `oq=` SRP URL param would get populated with

a non-empty string (the SRP URL itself) when initiating search queries

via zero-prefix suggestion clicks. The root cause of this issue is the

fact that we cannot assume that callers of ZeroSuggestProvider::Start()

will pass in an AutocompleteInput object with an empty `text_` field.



This CL addresses the issue by ensuring that all incoming inputs are

properly sanitized (i.e. GetZeroSuggestInput() is called) prior to

generating zero-prefix suggestions. Fixing this issue will ensure that

server-side logging is able to properly identify ZPS queries (i.e.

those which have an empty `oq=` value).

on SRP" flag set to "Enabled".

entry.title: gpu: win: Always use BGRA format for root surface
entry.content:
This change makes it so we always use BGRA formats for the root surface.

We previously used BGRX when the root pass had no alpha, which

eventually mapped to kRGB_888x_SkColorType and caused issues with

backdrop filter blur transitions. We are now passing the alpha type

separately from the format for render pass backing allocation, so we

can use a BGRA swap chain without incurring the cost of blending with

the destination during OS composition.



See: https://crrev.com/c/4337768

entry.title: [//gpu] Add glTexImage2DSharedImageCHROMIUM() GLES2 extension
entry.content:
This CL adds the following API to the GLES2 command decoders:



GLuint glTexImage2DSharedImageCHROMIUM (GLunit texture,

const GLbyte *mailbox)



`texture` is a client-side texture, and `mailbox` is the SharedImage to

assign to the first level of the texture.



This function maps `texture` to the texture object of the SharedImage

represented by the mailbox and ensures that if `texture` is bound to a

target, the service-side texture gets bound to that target.



On success, this function extends the lifetime of the SharedImage

referenced by mailbox by taking a ref. The texture object is deleted and

the ref released once the calling context deletes the texture name

associated with the texture object, and detaches it from all framebuffer

objects as well as texture unit bindings.



This CL also implements the new API in the passthrough decoder. The

implementation follows that of

glCreateAndTexStorage2DSharedImageCHROMIUM(), with the differences

being that



(a) the latter creates and returns a new client texture ID whereas the

new function uses the client texture ID passed in from the client

(b) TexImage2DSharedImageCHROMIUM() binds the client texture ID to the

target, as it might have previously been bound to a different

target.



Implementation in the validating decoder will happen as a followup.



This API will shortly be used to implement GPU-GPU copy of

VideoFrame textures to a WebGL texture via a temporary SharedImage that

is attached to that WebGL texture via this API.

entry.title: Use ToEnclosingRect() when transforming MaskFilterInfo instances
entry.content:
gfx::MaskFilterInfo, that holds a gfx::RRectF instance,

operates over ceiled bounds in both cc and viz, as seen [1][2],

for example.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/platform/widget/widget_base.cc;l=437?q=third_party%2Fblink%2Frenderer%2Fplatform%2Fwidget%2Fwidget_base.cc&ss=chromium

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/layers/layer_impl.cc;drc=80909977e0f2480462cedc4fc82a955c39d12bfd;l=163



The problem is that MaskFilterInfo itself holds un-ceiled values.

The occasional precision difference might result in having a 1-off

pixel visual discrepancies (see the referenced bugs below).



This CL calls gfx::ToEnclosingRect() right after transforming a MasfFilterInfo instance, so that it operates over ceiled bounds with

its value also ceiled.



In practice, it fixes is the alignment of pixels between content

and non-content areas (because rounded corners mask is also

results in clipping).

Moreover, it also helps to reduce the number of render passes as

viz refuses to merge mask filters that contain rounded corners

when a renderer also sets rounded corners. That is, when such a

content is at the border of a window, it can actually span outside

the non-content's rounder corner bounds.

Thus, making viz::CanMergeMaskFilterInfo fail and resulting in an

unnecessary render pass

entry.title: [iOS] Remove UrlLoadStrategy::ALWAYS_IN_INCOGNITO
entry.content:
The enum value UrlLoadStrategy::ALWAYS_IN_INCOGNITO was created to solve

the issue where the user opens tabs from "Context Menu -> History" when

the active tab is incognito. (crbug.com/960728 , with video of original

issue https://drive.google.com/open?id=1pPG2570Mn1-Y8GYplA5y3kguMHjyBd_2)



Recently, however, the "History" entry is removed for incognito mode

altogether (OverflowMenuMediator::destinationForDestinationType,

authored by @rkgibson in crrev/c/4602280) so the purpose of ALWAYS_IN_

INCOGNITO url load strategy is now obsolete.



This CL removes this enum to enhance code readability, otherwise future

developers may wonder why ALWAYS_IN_INCOGNITO and ALWAYS_NEW_FOREGROUD_

TAB are mutually exclusive (because they really should not be!)

entry.title: [v8 compile hints] Randomize the client-side data generation with less granularity
entry.content:
Per-page is too granular, because a page load might create caches which

another page load then uses. If the second page load decides to

generate compile hints data, they'll be corrupted because of the caches.
